10:49.116 --> 10:51.716
Test Pattern is an agreement,
a visual agreement,

10:51.718 --> 10:54.686
more than it is a group,
but we're still a group,

10:54.688 --> 10:57.756
I mean, we still consider
ourselves part of the...

10:57.758 --> 11:00.425
the art movement or the punk movement or...
or whatever it is.

11:00.427 --> 11:03.395
We still enjoy playing music
with each other.

11:03.397 --> 11:06.031
It's just that, at some point,

11:06.033 --> 11:09.100
you have to pull down
the curtain

11:09.102 --> 11:12.971
and put on our pajamas.

11:12.973 --> 11:17.375
♪ Found a roving spotlight. ♪

11:18.912 --> 11:22.947
♪ It's in my backyard. ♪

11:25.719 --> 11:28.053
They wrote about it
in the papers.

11:31.058 --> 11:34.392
♪ Meet me
at the designated spot. ♪

11:36.730 --> 11:39.731
♪ I'm alert! ♪

11:39.733 --> 11:42.400
- # I'm alert! #
- Give it to me.

11:42.402 --> 11:44.335
♪ I'm alert! ♪

11:44.337 --> 11:46.004
- One, two, three...
- # I'm alert! #

11:48.240 --> 11:52.410
Well, the group was starting
to sound really stale.

11:52.412 --> 11:54.946
It's very limiting
to have just guitars

11:54.948 --> 11:57.215
and electric bass and drums,

11:57.217 --> 12:02.087
and our producer, Ooto Keirsha,
played me this record,

12:02.089 --> 12:05.090
and it was gamelan music
from Bali,

12:05.092 --> 12:07.726
and I was really struck
by all the bells...

12:07.728 --> 12:09.327
It sounded like church bells
or something...

12:09.329 --> 12:11.429
and I went to the band
and I said,

12:11.431 --> 12:13.732
"This is what we should do,"
and they agreed

12:13.734 --> 12:15.934
and they nodded, and I said,

12:15.936 --> 12:18.870
"We're gonna incorporate
their music into our songs."

12:18.872 --> 12:20.505
Or, rather, my songs.

12:20.507 --> 12:24.776
The name of this song
is "In Ding, In Ding."

12:48.968 --> 12:52.170
I didn't love
the Balinese stuff.

12:52.172 --> 12:55.940
To be honest with you,
it wasn't my favorite.

12:55.942 --> 12:57.909
It just sounds like

12:57.911 --> 13:00.512
